Note:
x86_64 Assembly Generator - LIR to AT&T Syntax x86_64 Assembly

THE MOST CRITICAL FILE IN THE BACKEND.

Translates LIR instructions (opcodes 30000-30999) with physical register assignments
into AT&T syntax x86_64 assembly text. This is the primary code generation path for
the Runa compiler on Linux/WSL.

The generator processes an entire LIR module (collection of LIR functions), emitting:
- Function prologues (push rbp, adjust rsp, save callee-saved registers)
- Basic block labels
- Instruction-by-instruction translation of all ~100 LIR opcodes
- Function epilogues (restore callee-saved, restore rsp, pop rbp, ret)
- String literals in .rodata section
- Global variable declarations in .data/.bss sections

AT&T syntax conventions:
- Source before destination: movq %rax, %rbx (move rax INTO rbx)
- Register names prefixed with %: %rax, %rbp, %xmm0
- Immediates prefixed with $: $42, $0x1000
- Memory: displacement(%base, %index, scale) e.g., -16(%rbp), (%rax,%rbx,8)
- Size suffixes: b(byte), w(word), l(long/32-bit), q(quad/64-bit)

Dependencies:
- Imports LIR types for instructions, operands, functions, blocks
- Imports machine_code_interface for AssemblyOutput buffer management
- Imports calling convention for prologue/epilogue generation
- Imports string utilities for output buffer building
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir_nodes.runa" as LIRNodes
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/common/machine_code_interface.runa" as MachineCode
Import "compiler/backend/machine_code/x86_64/calling_convention.runa" as CallingConv
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dictionary
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils
Import "runtime/core/memory/chained_arena.runa" as ChainedArena

Note: ============================================================================
Note: x86_64 Assembly Generation Context
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The X86_64AsmContext holds all state needed during assembly generation for a module.
It wraps the AssemblyOutput buffer and adds x86_64-specific tracking:
- current_function: pointer to the LIR function being emitted
- convention: the calling convention info for the current function
- config: backend configuration (optimization level, PIC, debug, etc.)

The context is created once per module and reused across all functions.
@End Reasoning

Type called "X86_64AsmContext":
    output as Integer                 Note: Pointer to AssemblyOutput
    config as Integer                 Note: Pointer to BackendConfig
    current_function as Integer       Note: Pointer to current LIRFunction being emitted
    convention as Integer             Note: Pointer to CallingConventionInfo for current function
    arena as Integer                  Note: Arena for temporary allocations during generation
    error_count as Integer            Note: Number of errors encountered during generation
    string_buffer as Integer          Note: Temporary string buffer for building instruction text
End Type

Note: Size: 7 fields * 8 bytes = 56 bytes per X86_64AsmContext

Note: ============================================================================
Note: x86_64 GPR Name Tables (AT&T syntax)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
We need lookup tables mapping physical register IDs (0-15) to their AT&T syntax
names at different operand sizes. For example, register 0 (RAX) has names:
- 64-bit: %rax
- 32-bit: %eax
- 16-bit: %ax
- 8-bit:  %al

These tables are encoded as parallel lists indexed by register ID.
@End Reasoning

Process called "get_gpr_name_64" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the 64-bit AT&T register name string for a GPR (0-15)
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "%rax"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "%rbx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "%rcx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "%rdx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "%rsi"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "%rdi"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "%rbp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "%rsp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "%r8"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "%r9"
    End If
    If reg_id is 10:
        Return "%r10"
    End If
    If reg_id is 11:
        Return "%r11"
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return "%r12"
    End If
    If reg_id is 13:
        Return "%r13"
    End If
    If reg_id is 14:
        Return "%r14"
    End If
    If reg_id is 15:
        Return "%r15"
    End If
    Return "%rax"
End Process

Process called "get_gpr_name_32" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the 32-bit AT&T register name string for a GPR (0-15)
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "%eax"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "%ebx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "%ecx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "%edx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "%esi"
    End If
    If reg_id is 5:
        Return "%edi"
    End If
    If reg_id is 6:
        Return "%ebp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 7:
        Return "%esp"
    End If
    If reg_id is 8:
        Return "%r8d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 9:
        Return "%r9d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 10:
        Return "%r10d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 11:
        Return "%r11d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 12:
        Return "%r12d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 13:
        Return "%r13d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 14:
        Return "%r14d"
    End If
    If reg_id is 15:
        Return "%r15d"
    End If
    Return "%eax"
End Process

Process called "get_gpr_name_16" that takes reg_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Returns the 16-bit AT&T register name string for a GPR (0-15)
    If reg_id is 0:
        Return "%ax"
    End If
    If reg_id is 1:
        Return "%bx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 2:
        Return "%cx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 3:
        Return "%dx"
    End If
    If reg_id is 4:
        Return "%si"
